'''Forqn Group''' ({{lang-fa|گروه فرقان}}, named after [[Al-Furqan]] sura) was an [[Iran]]ian opposition militant group with [[clandestine cell system]] <ref name="P41"/> adhering to a [[Shia]] [[Anti-clericalism|anti-clerical]] [[Islamist]] ideology.

Furqan successfully assassinated some senior officials, including Gen. [[Valiollah Qarani]], [[Morteza Motahari]], [[Mohammad Mofatteh]] and [[Mohammad Ali Qazi Tabatabaei]]{{efn| Revolution Under Attack, [https://link.springer.com/book/10.1057%2F9781137502506 p.&nbsp;80]}} but it was soon terminated following arrest and execution of its key members in 1980.

The group opposed other social sectors such as the "wealthy ''[[bazaari]]s''", the "liberal
politicians" and the "Marxist atheists" who, in their view, "were plotting to betray the [[Islamic Revolution]]" .{{efn| Revolution Under Attack, [https://link.springer.com/book/10.1057%2F9781137502506 p.&nbsp;51-52]}}
The group self-proclaimed to be followers of [[Ali Shariati]], however claim was used instrumentally to look more "prestigious" and allow them to develop their combined ideology.{{efn| Revolution Under Attack, [https://link.springer.com/book/10.1057%2F9781137502506 p.&nbsp;76–77]}}

==Etymology==
Due to the literal meaning Forqan is described as criterion or standard. Proof or evidence is the meaning that [[Dictionary of Modern Written Arabic|Wehr's dictionary]] give to this word. Uri Rubin introduced Forquan  as one of names of the Quran. Muslim scholars believes that the root of this word is F.R.Q means depart. In the [[History of the Prophets and Kings|Tarikh al-Tabari]] and [[Tafsir al-Kabir (al-Razi)]] the  root of this word that means "to God's separating or distinguishing between truth and falsehood, is defined F.R.Q.<ref name="P41"/>{{Page needed|date=May 2017}}

==History==
The Forqan group is the Islamic shia group that  emphasized the Islam without clergy and decided to present the real Islam and truthful message of [[Quran]].<ref name="Shahidi">{{cite book|last1=Shahidi|first1=Hossein|title=Journalism in Iran: From Mission to Profession|date=2007|publisher=Routledge; Reissue edition|isbn=978-0415583169|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MLLywtI-_n0C&pg=PA34&lpg=PA34&dq=The+Forqan+Group+of+Iran&source=bl&ots=pmoUHOsVF8&sig=1z24-V7UeHdSTKfcFxSNpYMGbRA&hl=fa&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwip3K2WybzTAhXrBZoKHYoDByg4ChDoAQg4MAc#v=onepage&q=The%20Forqan%20Group%20of%20Iran&f=false}}</ref>

According to the [[Ali Shariati|Shariati]]' thought, the rule of the unity of Allah forms the basic element of an equal and just society in the [[Muhammad|Muhammad prophet]]'s tradition. He believed that  [[the Twelve Imams]] (not [[Rashidun]] except [[Ali]]) are the real successors of the Prophet and they tried to make equal society. Also he considered [[shia Islam]] above all ideologies  and religions but clerics should not have key role at political positions. Akbar Goodarzi who were affected by revolutionary thought of Shariati, authored interpretation of the [[Quran]] named monotheistic ideology. Shariati  followed Islamic method without clerical intervention such as [[Abul A'la Maududi ]]'s idea but Goodarzi was more fanatical than Shariati  and on 1970 the Forqan group was founded by him. Another person who had important effect on forming the ideology of Forqan group was Habibollah Ashory, the frustrated cleric.<ref name="P41"/>{{Page needed|date=May 2017}}

The climax of activities of Forqan group, actually the fight against clericalism is seen at early days after victory of Iranian  revolution and finally this group in early1980 was eliminated by arresting members of it.<ref name="P41"/>{{Page needed|date=May 2017}}<ref name="jamejam"/>

==Activities== 
The Forqan group was a radical Iranian organization that claimed responsibility for a number of assassinations during the 1979 Revolution. <ref>"[https://www.encyclopedia.com/humanities/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/forqan Forqan]." Encyclopedia of the Modern Middle East and North Africa. . Encyclopedia.com. 23 Nov. 2018</ref> The responsibilities of following assassinated persons had been undertaken by this group:<ref name="jamejam">{{cite web|last1=Staff|first1=Writer|title=Take a look to assassinations of Forqan groupe|url=http://www1.jamejamonline.ir/papertext.aspx?newsnum=100875654357|website=jamejamonline|date=2010}}</ref><ref name="Shahidi"/>
[[Mohammad-Vali Gharani]], [[Morteza Motahhari]],<ref name="E. Marty">{{cite book|last1=E. Marty|first1=Martin|last2=Appleby|first2=R. Scott|last3=H. Garvey|first3=John|last4=Kuran|first4=Timur|title=Fundamentalisms and the State: Remaking Polities, Economies, and Militance|date=1996|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0226508849|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=doCmVaOnh_wC&pg=PA524&lpg=PA524&dq=terrors+of+forqan+group&source=bl&ots=NNyy-G2Ofo&sig=PAtEvQrt6-73St6hLVZ4oeVvwsc&hl=fa&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjgmfLMg8nTAhUlJpoKHWDSCYwQ6AEISTAG#v=onepage&q=terrors%20of%20forqan%20group&f=false}}</ref> [[Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani ]],<ref name="E. Marty"/> Mohammad Taghi Haji Tarkhani, [[Abbas Amir-Entezam]], Seyed Razi Shirazi, Seyed Mohsen Behbahani, Hosein Mahdian, Mahdi Iraqi, Hesam Iraqi, Mohammad Baqir Dashtianeh, Hans Joachim Leib, [[Mohammad Ali Qazi Tabatabaei]], [[Mohammad Mofatteh]], Javad Bahmani, Asghar Nemati, Faqih Imani and Qasim Rouhani.

The assassination attempts on prominent Iranians [http://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1979/08/09/staff-of-iranian-newspaper-faces-trial/23b3280d-66c5-456c-bada-45c4aada0ce1/?tid=ss_mail&utm_term=.4d9b2ac63db6 Ahmad Ladjevardi <ref>{{cite news |publisher=The Washington Post |last=Cumming-Bruce |first=Nicholas |date=August 9, 1979 |title=Staff of Iranian Newspaper Faces Trial |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1979/08/09/staff-of-iranian-newspaper-faces-trial/23b3280d-66c5-456c-bada-45c4aada0ce1/?utm_term=.4d9b2ac63db6}}</ref>], [[Ali Khamenei]] and [[Abdul-Karim Mousavi Ardebili]] were attributed to furqan group.<ref name="jamejam"/><ref name="Alavi">{{cite web|last1=Alavi|first1=Hamid|title=Assassination attempt on Ali Khamenei 35 years later|url=http://www.bbc.com/persian/iran/2016/06/160626_l10_ha_khamenei_assassination_attempt|website=BBC}}</ref>

